East 37th Street, n.s., w. from no. 103, Manhattan
ca. 1902

Gift of Catherine C. (Mrs. Charles D.) Dickey,
Chestnut Hill, Philadelphia, Penna., Sept 1971

Park Avenue, adjoining the N.E. corner of E. 37th Street, showing at this location the garden established in 1913-16 by the Murray Hill Association to remedy the unsightly appearance of this vacant lot, the property of the I.R.T. Co. In 1923 this will be included in the site for the 15 story
apartment house, No. 6l Park Avenue.
Thru the center runs Park Avenue and to the left is E. 37th Street, west of the Avenue. In 1931 the Union League Club House will rise there. Opposite same and prominently shown is the building at the N.W. corner occupied by Charles Coaster and which has recently (N.Y. Sun June 14, 1939) been sold for replacement by an apartment house. This is to be of Georgian design and
harmonize with the Union League Club building.

237 Est 37th Street, West side, showing the Murray
Hill Vocational #P.S.49.
Board of Education, of N.Y.C.

45 Park Avenue, "The Russell", at S.E. corner of 37th Street, an apartment hotel newly erected on the site of the old Judge Russell residence.
In the foreground it will be noted that the center parks are being altered slightly, for the first time since 1650 or earlier.
1923.
Joseph Smith, Photographer.
Gift of E.M. Jenks.

Park Avenue, at, adjoining and north of the N.W. corner of East 37th Street. Prominently shown is the new apartment structure, No. 50 Park Avenue. At the left margin appears a portion of the Union League Club.
April 26, 1940
George D. Chinn

Park Avenue, west side, from E. 37th to 38th Streets, as viewed northwestward from the east side of this thoroughfare and showing in addition (left) the north side of 37th Street,
west froom Park to Madison Avenues.
The New York Times of June 14, 1939, reportsathe sale for improvement of the corner property and the adjoining three structures on 37th Street. Cromorising same are the Charles Coster house (50 Pnrk Avenue), the former home of General Charles P. Roe of the N. Y. S. N. G. (No. 35 E. 37th Street), the Cortlandt F(e1d Bishop home (No. 33 E.) and the Issac W. How home (No. 31 E.). The latter was sold by the estate nf William M. Savin and No's 33
and 35 by Miss Sarah Ahern.
At the extreme left of View 1 is the National Democratic Club, located at the N. E. corner (Gf E. 37th Street and Madison Avenue. View No. 2 is westward on 37th Street while No. 3 fs southwestward to include the Union League Club (1931) at the S. W.
corner and opposite this new project.
Overhead appears the tower of the Empire State Building and a cornice of the Engineering Combustion Building.
View 1: June 14, 1931
View 2: April 15, 1931
View 3: Sept. 9, 1933

(1)
Park Avenue, north from and including 38th Street, seen from 37th Street, and showing the west side of the Avenue.

The white building on the N.W. corner of 38th Street is the 70 Park Avenue Hotel. Above it is the Princeton Club on the N.W. corner of 39th Street, and the Murray Hill Hotel from 40th to 41st Streets. The Hotel Belmont, rising behind the Murray Hill, is to be demolished in 1931, as are the buildings on the S.W. corner of 40th Street.

To the left of the Belmont may be seen part of the old Lincoln Bank Building about to be demolished to make way for the new Lincoln Building at 60 East 42nd Street.

The avenue is cut off by the Grand Central Station, with the New York Central Building rising directly behind it.

March 10, 1929.

P. L. Sperr, Photographer.

(2)
The same, but also showing the east side of the Avenue, and a close view of the center parks as they have appeared since modernization in 1923. Compare this with the 1929 picture on this mount. The Lincoln Building towers behind the Princeton Club and the Murray Hill Hotel. The buildings on the S.W. corner of 39th Street, demolished 1933, have been replaced by a parking place for automobiles -- the wire fence is visible to a sharp eye. The old houses on the S.W. corner of 40th Street were replaced in 1933 by the low, white commercial structure visible between the Princeton Club and the murray Hill Hotel.

On the east side of the Avenue the houses on the N.W. corner of 39th Street have been demolished, but the Little House, which replaces them, is set back too far from the street to be visible in this picture.

March 22, 1935.

P. L. Sperr, Photographer.

Park Avenue, east side, from 37th to 4lst Streets, but not showing the small building on the N.E. corner of 41st Street. No. 55 Park Avenue, in the right foreground, was built in 1923 on the site of the old Interborough Garden shown in another picture. From 38th to 39th Streets are shown the new apartment buildings built between 1922 and 1924, and behind them the towers of the Chanin and Chrysler Buildings. On the N.E. corner of 39th Street the old houses are being demolished. The tall white building on the N.E. corner of 40th Street is the architects' Building, erected in 1916.
September 10, 1933.
P. L. Sperr, Photographer.

Park Ave. (left), at the S.W. corner of East 37th Street, showing the Union League Club. The club was organised in 1863 and most of its members are politically of Republican proclivities. This is its fourth
building.
1936.
W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Writers Project.

Park Ave., west side, south from but not including East 40th to East 37th Streets, showing W.P.A. employees engaged in converting the former railroad and afterward street car tunnel under Park Ave. for vehicular use. The 4-story building (No. 86 Park Ave., at the N.W. corner of East 39th Street) prominently shown on the right.is the Princeton Club.
May 6, 1936.
W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Art Project.

Park Ave., at East 37th Street, showing the tablet erected by the D.A.R. to Mary Lindley Murray. This marker is placed in the grass plot
that divides the traffic lanes of this thoroughfare.
September 8, 1937.
George D. Chinn.

E. 37th Street, north side, west of Second Avenue. Adjoining the corner is the Murray Hill Industrial High School. Adjacent to same is the newly erected portion of the New York Telephone Co. building. This replaced two former tenements, No's 229 and 231. At Lexington Avenue appears the rear of the Hotel White. Note the
grade,giving this area its long familiar name.
January 8, 1939
Somach Photo Service
New York City Tunnel Authority
